Here's a basic example of a C++ function that could convert a markdown-formatted string to an html-formatted string. It is important to note that markdown can be quite complex and this function only handles headers and paragraphs:

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHTML(std::string& md) {
    std::string html = md;

    // Convert headers
    std::regex headerPattern("^(#{1,6}) (.*)$");
    std::smatch match;
    while (std::regex_search(html, match, headerPattern)) {
        int level = match.str(1).length();
        html.replace(match.position(), match.length(), "<h" + std::to_string(level) + ">" + match.str(2) + "</h" + std::to_string(level) + ">");
    }

    // Convert paragraphs
    std::regex paragraphPattern("^(?!<h.*>$)(.*)$");
    while (std::regex_search(html, match, paragraphPattern)) {
        html.replace(match.position(), match.length(), "<p>" + match.str(1) + "</p>");
    }

    return html;
}
```

This function uses regular expressions to search for markdown syntax in the input string and replace it with the corresponding HTML syntax. Headers are defined in markdown by beginning a line with one to six '#' characters, followed by a space and the header text. Paragraphs are simply lines of text that are not headers.

This is a very basic implementation and doesn't handle many of the other features of markdown, such as links, images, lists, and more. For a full markdown to HTML converter, you might want to use a library such as `cmark`, the official C implementation of CommonMark.

